# 15. Risks & Best Practices

## 15.1 Risk Register

| Risk | L | I | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Rules sheet edited incorrectly (bad threshold) | M | H | RF change log tab + effective dating; QA validates compute used current effective rules; future: SharePoint approval on edits |
| Router misclassification sends request to wrong domain | M | M | Confidence < 0.6 → CLARIFY; router accuracy tracked in metrics; misroutes correctable by user in one turn |
| Stale KB doc makes AI confidently wrong | M | H | Quarterly review cadence + stale-knowledge alerts; QA Q5 verifies citations against actual retrieval; deprecated docs auto-purged from index |
| LLM QA false positives block good output | M | M | Deterministic checks carry 2× weight; Haiku-first with Sonnet escalation on UNCERTAIN; thresholds tuned after 20 production runs |
| Retry loops raise cost | L | M | Hard cap 2; commentary-only retries skip recompute; retries logged + alerted |
| Token budget creep as KB grows | M | M | Assembler hard-trims to 3,000 input tokens; overflow metric alerts; retrieval capped at 5 chunks |
| Google OAuth silent expiry | M | M | Known symptom documented (all-branches-not-found); alert on that signature; quarterly reconnect calendar |
| Config sheet as single point of failure | L | H | Nightly config export to GitHub (versioned backup); cache serves last-good on read failure |
| n8n task-runner binary/module constraints (known) | — | — | Already mitigated: `N8N_DEFAULT_BINARY_DATA_MODE=default`; binary via `$input.all()`; SheetJS accepted until Office Script migration |

## 15.2 Best Practices (operating rules)

1. **Deterministic-first, always.** New capability = compute module first, AI commentary second, QA checks third — in that order.
2. **Config before code.** If a value could change, it goes in the registry on day one.
3. **One concept per KB chunk; five great docs beat fifty mediocre ones.**
4. **Never trust an untested threshold.** QA and router thresholds are tuned against labeled fixtures before production reliance.
5. **Version everything, log versions everywhere.** Every run records rule, template, and module versions — that's what makes an audit answerable.
6. **Escalation is a feature.** A run held for human review is the system working, not failing.

